<p>
  I started brainstorming and designing this conceptual budget app after being an avid user of <a href="http://www.dailybudget.de/" target="_blank">Daily Budget</a>.
</p>

<h2>Inspiration</h2>
<p>
  One of the first things I struggled with after graduating from college was budgeting. "Saving up" was a common concept but "budgeting" seemed so foreign. I knew I wanted to save up but I didn't know how.
</p>

<p>
  So I tried a few budgeting apps. I wanted to focus on saving up. Many apps focused on spending analysis (which I didn't need much since I already knew where I spent more than I should -- coffee and shopping), while lacking in core, simple budgeting features. Also, those apps wanted to automate everything and wanted more information than what I was comfortable providing. Overall, those apps felt much heavier than what I needed them to be while not getting the core budget functionality right.
</p>

<p>The problem I wanted to solve was to create a budgeting app that fit the following criteria:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Easy to create a budget and add expenses and income</li>
  <li>No need to link my cards and banking information</li>
  <li>No signing up</li>
  <!-- <li>Support budget sharing with others (e.g. significant other)</li> -->
</ul>

<h2>Design Process</h2>
<p>There were multiple facets to the product: onboarding, recording spendings, analytics, and connecting with other devices. It was important to carefully adjust to these layers but keep the design simple and quickly learnable.</p>

